SRM img generation¶

This notebook performs SRM on the brain data to align it into the same space and then runs the same neural net as above to recreate images ¶

Now lets use SRM to see if we can improve these elementary results using all subs

# First SRM is a 2000 feature SRM
features = 2000
# Download if already preprocessed
try:
    all_sub_SRM_train = np.load(f'np_data/{features}_SRM_all_subs_train.npy')
    all_sub_images_train = np.load('np_data/all_sub_images_train.npy')
    all_sub_labels_train = np.load('np_data/all_sub_labels_train.npy')
    all_sub_SRM_test = np.load(f'np_data/{features}_SRM_all_subs_test.npy')
    all_sub_images_test = np.load('np_data/all_sub_images_test.npy')
    all_sub_labels_test = np.load('np_data/all_sub_labels_test.npy')
    
# Else make the data
except FileNotFoundError:
    for tag in ['train', 'test']:
        # load the data
        num_subs = 3
        labels = []
        fmri = []
        images = []
        for i in range(1, num_subs+1): # Loading the data
            labels.append(np.load(f"np_data/sub_0{i}_labels_{tag}.npy"))
            fmri.append(np.load(f"np_data/sub_0{i}_fmri_{tag}.npy"))
            images.append(np.load(f"np_data/sub_0{i}_images_{tag}.npy"))


        # Data is not sorted. Images where shown in random order. We have to make some alignments. 
        for i in range(num_subs):
            indexed_sort = np.argsort(labels[i])
            labels[i] = labels[i][indexed_sort]
            fmri[i] = fmri[i][indexed_sort]
            images[i] = images[i][indexed_sort]

        images = np.array(images)
        labels = np.array(labels)

        # Fmri has differing lengths, have to keep as a list
        # Also, reorganizing to fit SRM
        for subj in range(len(fmri)):
            fmri[subj] = np.transpose(fmri[subj], (1, 0))

        # Create the SRM object
        if tag == 'train':
            srm = brainiak.funcalign.srm.SRM(n_iter=20, features=features)
            print("fitting SRM")
            srm.fit(fmri)
            print("SRM has been fit")

        transformed_data = srm.transform(fmri)
        all_sub_SRM = np.concatenate(np.array(transformed_data), axis = 1)
        all_sub_SRM = stats.zscore(all_sub_SRM, axis = 1)
        all_sub_SRM = np.transpose(all_sub_SRM, (1, 0)) # Turning it back into n * features
        all_sub_images = np.concatenate(images, axis = 0)    
        all_sub_labels = np.concatenate(labels, axis = 0)

        # Saving
        np.save(f'np_data/{features}_SRM_all_subs_{tag}.npy', all_sub_SRM)
        np.save(f'np_data/all_sub_images_{tag}.npy', all_sub_images)
        np.save(f'np_data/all_sub_labels_{tag}.npy', all_sub_labels)

Reminder that we train and test on the training data because the test data contains unseen classes. This will be useful in our image generation, but it makes testing on it impossible. Further, the way that we sub sample the training data avoids any double dipping.

In [43]:
accuracies = []
train_split = 0.8
# Define the classifier
clf = svm.SVC(gamma = 'auto')


for i in tqdm(range(1000)):
    ss = np.random.randint(1, 1200, size = 2) # taking a subsample of 2 categories
    if ss[0] == ss[1]: # so we don't sample twice the same number
        ss[1] = ss[0]+1
    ss_coords = np.in1d(all_sub_labels_train, ss).nonzero()[0] # getting coords for all occurences of the class
    shuffle = np.random.permutation(len(ss_coords)) # shuffle
    labels_ss = (all_sub_labels_train[ss_coords])
    fmri_ss = (all_sub_SRM_train[ss_coords])

    # keeping the training and test data balanced
    x_len = int(len(labels_ss)*train_split/2) # Number of vals in each class to train on
    mask = np.hstack([np.random.choice(np.where(labels_ss == _class)[0], x_len, replace=False)
                      for _class in np.unique(labels_ss)])
    
    # Extract 
    selected = np.where(~np.in1d(np.arange(len(labels_ss)), mask))[0]
    train_x, train_y = fmri_ss[mask], labels_ss[mask]
    test_x, test_y = fmri_ss[selected], labels_ss[selected]
    clf.fit(train_x, train_y)
    accuracies.extend((clf.predict(test_x) == test_y))
    
print(f"yielding us {sum(accuracies)/len(accuracies)} in a binary classification task")

clf = svm.SVC(gamma = 'auto')

for i in tqdm(range(1000)):
    ss = np.random.randint(1, 1200, size = 2) # taking a subsample of 2 categories
    if ss[0] == ss[1]: # so we don't sample twice the same number
        ss[1] = ss[0]+1
    ss_coords = np.in1d(all_sub_labels_train, ss).nonzero()[0] # getting coords for all occurences of the class
    shuffle = np.random.permutation(len(ss_coords)) # shuffle
    labels_ss = (all_sub_labels_train[ss_coords])
    fmri_ss = (SRM_train_new[ss_coords])

    # keeping the training and test data balanced
    x_len = int(len(labels_ss)*train_split/2) # Number of vals in each class to train on
    mask = np.hstack([np.random.choice(np.where(labels_ss == _class)[0], x_len, replace=False)
                      for _class in np.unique(labels_ss)])
    
    # Extract 
    selected = np.where(~np.in1d(np.arange(len(labels_ss)), mask))[0]
    train_x, train_y = fmri_ss[mask], labels_ss[mask]
    test_x, test_y = fmri_ss[selected], labels_ss[selected]
    clf.fit(train_x, train_y)
    accuracies.extend((clf.predict(test_x) == test_y))

We get the exact same accuracy as above with one twentieth of the features. This is a very efficient classifier. However, one concerning aspect is that classification accuracy should not be so high on brain data. I am afraid that we may have some double dipping occuring. It's hard to say since I did not preprocess this data. This may pose an issue going forward. If there is double dipping then it is possible that the features that have been extracted are not explanatory of the image, but instead are useful in memorizing which labels match to which data.


Regardless, we have to soldier on!

class DataModule(pl.LightningDataModule):
    @staticmethod
    def get_HP(args = []):
        parser = argparse.ArgumentParser(description='Define model Hyperparams')
        root_dir = os.getcwd()
        parser.add_argument('--embed_size', default = 300)
        parser.add_argument('--X_train', default=os.path.join(root_dir, 'np_data/300_SRM_all_subs_train.npy'), type=str)
        parser.add_argument('--X_test', default=os.path.join(root_dir, 'np_data/300_SRM_all_subs_test.npy'), type=str)
        parser.add_argument('--y_train', default=os.path.join(root_dir, 'np_data/all_sub_images_train.npy'), type=str)
        parser.add_argument('--y_test', default=os.path.join(root_dir, 'np_data/all_sub_images_test.npy'), type=str)
        parser.add_argument('--data_dir', default=os.path.join(root_dir, 'data/SRM_gen'), type=str)
        return parser.parse_args(args = args)
    
    def __init__(self, HP):
        super().__init__()
        self.HP = HP

    # For one time preprocessing of data
    def prepare_data(self):
        try: # Check if the data has already been preprocessed
            temp = torch.load(self.HP.data_dir + '/test.h5'); del temp;
        except:
            X_train = np.load(self.HP.X_train)
            y_train = np.load(self.HP.y_train)
            X_test = np.load(self.HP.X_test)
            y_test = np.load(self.HP.y_test)

            # Creating the dataset
            X_train = torch.reshape(torch.Tensor(X_train), (-1, self.HP.embed_size, 1, 1)) # transform to torch tensor# transform to torch tensor
            X_test = torch.reshape(torch.Tensor(X_test), (-1, self.HP.embed_size, 1, 1)) 

            #ims train
            y_train_resized = []
            for img in y_train:
                img = Image.fromarray(img)
                img = img.resize((32, 32), Image.BICUBIC)
                y_train_resized.append(np.array(img).transpose(2, 0, 1))
            y_train = torch.Tensor(np.stack(y_train_resized, axis=0))/255

            #ims test
            y_test_resized = []
            for img in y_test:
                img = Image.fromarray(img)
                img = img.resize((32, 32), Image.BICUBIC)
                y_test_resized.append(np.array(img).transpose(2, 0, 1))
            y_test = torch.Tensor(np.stack(y_test_resized, axis=0))/255
            if not os.path.exists(self.HP.data_dir):
                os.mkdir(self.HP.data_dir)
            torch.save({"X": X_train, "y": y_train}, self.HP.data_dir + '/train.h5')
            torch.save({"X": X_test, "y": y_test}, self.HP.data_dir + '/test.h5')    

    def setup(self, stage=None):
        train = torch.load(self.HP.data_dir + '/train.h5')
        self.train_ds = TensorDataset(train["X"], train["y"])
        test = torch.load(self.HP.data_dir + '/test.h5')
        self.test_ds = TensorDataset(test["X"], test["y"])
        
    def train_dataloader(self):
        return DataLoader(self.train_ds, batch_size=64, pin_memory=True, shuffle=True) # create your dataloader

    def val_dataloader(self):
        return DataLoader(self.test_ds, batch_size=64, shuffle=True) # create your dataloader)
    
    def test_dataloader(self):
        return DataLoader(self.test_ds, batch_size=10, shuffle=True) # create your dataloader)
    

        
class Generator(pl.LightningModule):
    @staticmethod
    def get_HP(args = []):
        parser = argparse.ArgumentParser(description='Define model Hyperparams')
        root_dir = os.getcwd()
        parser.add_argument('--embed_size', default = 300)
        parser.add_argument('--ngf', default = 64)
        return parser.parse_args(args = args)
    
    def __init__(self, HP):
        super().__init__()
        self.HP = HP
        self.save_hyperparameters()
        self.main = nn.Sequential(
            # input is Z, going into a convolution
            nn.ConvTranspose2d(HP.embed_size, HP.ngf * 8, 4, 1, 0, bias=False),
            nn.BatchNorm2d(HP.ngf * 8),
            nn.ReLU(True),
            # state size. (ngf*8) x 4 x 4
            nn.ConvTranspose2d(HP.ngf * 8, HP.ngf * 4, 4, 2, 1, bias=False),
            nn.BatchNorm2d(HP.ngf * 4),
            nn.ReLU(True),
            # state size. (ngf*4) x 8 x 8
            nn.ConvTranspose2d(HP.ngf * 4, HP.ngf * 2, 4, 2, 1, bias=False),
            nn.BatchNorm2d(HP.ngf * 2),
            nn.ReLU(True),
            # state size. (ngf*2) x 16 x 16
            nn.ConvTranspose2d(HP.ngf * 2, HP.ngf, 4, 2, 1, bias=False),
            nn.BatchNorm2d(HP.ngf),
            nn.ReLU(True),
            nn.ConvTranspose2d(HP.ngf, 3, kernel_size=1, stride=1, padding=0, bias=False),
            nn.Sigmoid()
        )
        
    def configure_optimizers(self):
        optimizer = torch.optim.Adam(self.parameters(), lr=1e-3)
        return optimizer
    
    def forward(self, x):
        return self.main(x)
    
    def training_step(self, batch, batch_idx):
        fmri, ims = batch
        gen = self(fmri)
        loss = F.mse_loss(gen, ims)
        self.log('train_loss', loss, )
        return loss
    
    def validation_step(self, batch, batch_idx):
        fmri, ims = batch
        gen = self(fmri)
        loss = F.mse_loss(gen, ims)
        self.log('val_loss', loss, prog_bar=True)
    
    def test_step(self, batch, batch_idx):
        fmri, ims = batch
        gen = self(fmri)
        loss = F.mse_loss(gen, ims)
        self.predictions = gen
        self.targets = ims
        self.log('test_loss', loss)
    

early_stop_callback = EarlyStopping(
   monitor='train_loss',
   min_delta=0,
   patience=30,
   verbose=False,
   mode='min'
)    

# saves a file like: my/path/sample-mnist-epoch=02-val_loss=0.32.ckpt
checkpoint_callback = ModelCheckpoint(
    save_last=True,
    save_top_k=1,
    mode='min',
    monitor='train_loss',
    filename='nueroImg-{epoch:02d}-{train_loss:.4f}'
)

dm_HP = DataModule.get_HP()
dm = DataModule(dm_HP)

"""
Running our model
"""
model_HP = Generator.get_HP()
model = Generator(model_HP)

trainer = pl.Trainer(max_epochs=200, gpus=1, callbacks=[checkpoint_callback, early_stop_callback])
trainer.fit(model, dm)
